<leg:level id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R28-1"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="rul" searchtype="LEGISLATION RUL" subdoc="true" toc-caption="[r 28.1] r 28.1 Definition (cf SCR Part 31, rule 1) ">
<leg:levelinfo>
<leg:levelstatus isrepealed="false" ln.user-displayed="false"/></leg:levelinfo>
<leg:heading inline="true"><edpnum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R28-1" type="ext"/>[r 28.1]</edpnum><title searchtype="RUL-TITLE">Definition (cf SCR Part 31, rule 1) </title><desig searchtype="RUL-NUM"><designum>28.1</designum></desig></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:bodytext>
<p><text>In this Part, <defterm><emph typestyle="bf">question</emph></defterm> includes any question or issue in any proceedings, whether of fact or law or partly of fact and partly of law, and whether raised by pleadings, agreement of parties or otherwise.</text></p>
<leg:comntry subdoc="true" toc-caption="NOTE"><heading searchtype="COMMENTARY"><title><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.PT28.R1.COM1" type="ext"/>NOTE</title></heading>
<level id="UCPN_UCPR.SGM_UCPN.UCPR.28-1-5" leveltype="para0" subdoc="true" toc-caption="[28.1.5] Scope of the power to consolidate or order separate determination"><heading searchtype="COMMENTARY"><edpnum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.28-1-5" type="ext"/>[28.1.5] </edpnum><title>Scope of the power to consolidate or order separate determination</title></heading>
<bodytext searchtype="COMMENTARY">
<p>
<text>The rules in this Part deal with: (1) separate trials of particular questions; and (2) consolidation. Although both procedures can be effectively used in appropriate circumstances, a degree of practical scepticism surrounds the use of both.
At least where the proposed separate determination relates to limited issues in the proceedings, difficulties in the formulation of the issue, identification of the relevant evidence, as well as the practical significance of the issue for the proceedings as a whole risk procedural complexities and costs that outweigh the apparent attraction of the procedure. This is particularly so where the credit of the witnesses will be as relevant on the preliminary point as on any subsequent hearing. Different complications arise in the case of consolidation. Where there are significant differences in the parties to proceedings, it is often more simple and appropriate for parties to agree that one set of proceedings be run as a test case than have a formal consolidation of proceedings.</text></p>
</bodytext>
